# Modelfile — builds the `qwen3.6-coder` agent driver for Ollama.
#
#   ollama create qwen3.6-coder -f Modelfile
#
# Driver model: Qwen 3.6-27B dense at 4-bit (~16 GB). On a 48 GB Apple Silicon
# Mac this fits comfortably alongside a long KV cache, and it has the best
# tool-calling reliability of anything that fits 48 GB.

# --- Base ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Preferred: the Unsloth MTP GGUF build. It adds the `developer` role that
# OpenCode relies on, and ships MTP (multi-token prediction) speculative
# decoding for a 1.4–2.2x speed-up with no accuracy loss. It is stable now
# (no longer experimental) and llama.cpp has merged MTP support.
FROM hf.co/unsloth/Qwen3.6-27B-MTP-GGUF:Q4_K_M

# Simpler fallback if you don't need the developer role / MTP — the stock
# Ollama-library build. Comment out the FROM above and uncomment this one:
# FROM qwen3.6:27b-q4_K_M

# --- Context window -----------------------------------------------------------
# CRITICAL: Ollama defaults num_ctx to 4096, which silently truncates the system
# prompt + tool schemas and makes tool use fail intermittently with no error.
# 48 GB carries the 27B at 4-bit plus a long KV cache, so give it real room.
PARAMETER num_ctx 65536

# --- Sampling -----------------------------------------------------------------
# Low temperature for deterministic, reliable code + tool calls.
PARAMETER temperature 0.2
PARAMETER top_p 0.9

# --- MTP speculative decoding (Unsloth GGUF path) -----------------------------
# When using the Unsloth MTP GGUF above, MTP is carried inside the GGUF and is
# used automatically by a recent llama.cpp / Ollama (0.19+). There is no extra
# Modelfile flag to set. To confirm it is active, watch `ollama serve` logs for
# the MTP / draft-decoding lines, or benchmark tokens/s against the plain
# `qwen3.6:27b` build — you should see ~1.4x+ faster generation.
